05862nam a22007695i 9780226768359DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020043576  a9780226768359  a(DE-B1597)588997  a(OCoLC)1246583581  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aML3917.U6b.B87 2021 4aML3917.U6b.B87 2021 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a781.66090462231 aBurke, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTear Down the Walls :bWhite Radicalism and Black Power in 1960s Rock /cPatrick Burke. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b18 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Honkie Soul: Th e MC5 at the Democratic National Convention— Lincoln Park, Chicago, August 25, 1968 -- t2. Blue Eyes and a Black Face: Jeff erson Airplane and the Rock Revolution— Th e Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour (CBS- TV), November 10, 1968 -- t3. One Plus One: Jean- Luc Godard Meets the Rolling Stones— London Film Festival, November 29, 1968 -- t4. The Seats Belong to the People: Th e Battle of the Fillmore East— Lower East Side, Manhattan, December 26, 1968 -- t5. Declare the Nation into Being: Woodstock and the Movement— Woodstock Music & Art Fair, White Lake, NY, August 15– 18, 1969 -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the earliest days of rock and roll, white artists regularly achieved fame, wealth, and success that eluded the Black artists whose work had preceded and inspired them. This dynamic continued into the 1960s, even as the music and its fans grew to be more engaged with political issues regarding race. In Tear Down the Walls, Patrick Burke tells the story of white American and British rock musicians’ engagement with Black Power politics and African American music during the volatile years of 1968 and 1969. The book sheds new light on a significant but overlooked facet of 1960s rock—white musicians and audiences casting themselves as political revolutionaries by enacting a romanticized vision of African American identity. These artists’ attempts to cast themselves as revolutionary were often naïve, misguided, or arrogant, but they could also reflect genuine interest in African American music and culture and sincere investment in anti-racist politics. White musicians such as those in popular rock groups Jefferson Airplane, the Rolling Stones, and the MC5, fascinated with Black performance and rhetoric, simultaneously perpetuated a long history of racial appropriation and misrepresentation and made thoughtful, self-aware attempts to respectfully present African American music in forms that white leftists found politically relevant. In Tear Down the Walls Patrick Burke neither condemns white rock musicians as inauthentic nor elevates them as revolutionary. The result is a fresh look at 1960s rock that provides new insight into how popular music both reflects and informs our ideas about race and how white musicians and activists can engage meaningfully with Black political movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBlack powerzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlack power-United States-History-20th century. 0aMusic and racezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusic and race-United States-History-20th century. 0aRock musicxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRock musiczUnited StatesxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aRock musiczUnited Statesy1961-1970xHistory and criticism. 0aRock music-United States-1961-1970-History and criticism. 0aRock music-United States-Social aspects-History